          "body": "The triad's ratios are not incidental. 1-in-100 (sheep, ~1%), 1-in-10 (coin, 10%), 1-in-2 (son, 50%). With each parable the value of the one increases and the personal stake of the seeker deepens. The shepherd loses *something he owns*; the woman loses *something necessary for living* (a *drachme* was a day's wage); the father loses *someone he loves*. The escalation peaks when Jesus reveals the second lost son — the elder brother — at which point the Pharisees themselves are inside the parable, not outside it. The argument's structure is pastorally devastating: agree with parables 1 and 2, and you are bound to the verdict of parable 3."
